questiontext.text:
Let's consider a survey conducted with 100 farms to gather information about their crop habits. Each farm was asked three specific questions regarding Maize, Sorghum, and Millet.

  1. Did they grow the crop last year?
  2. If yes, did the crop succeed enough to be sold?
  3. If sold, what was their profit?


Use the data provided to determine:

1.   (a) Which crop was the most profitable on average?

[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]

(b) Which one was the least profitable on average?

[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]

[[feedback:prt1]]


2. What is the mean profit for {@q2_crop@}?

[[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]]

[[feedback:prt3]]

truefeedback.text:
It appears that all of the missing values have been ignored in this question. However, we are looking at the most profitable crop. There are some crops which were grown which were not sold. Arguably the missing values in the profit columns therefore do have a value that we can give them.

Alternatively, to get this answer it is possible that you have replaced the missing values with a different value, such as the mean. What value have you replaced them with? Does that make sense in this context? The mean, for example, might not make sense here. It is not that the profit is unknown, it is that there was no money made at all.

It appears that you have correctly identified to fill in the missing values. However, check the value that you are using to replace the missing values with. Does that make sense in this context? It is not that the profit is unknown, it is that there was no money made at all.

It appears that one of two things has happened here. We recommend looking at the averages not the sum, this is due to a difference in group sizes.

Alternatively, if you are looking at averages then it is great you have identified that the missing values in the profit columns do have a value that we can give them. However, it is incorrect that all missing values have a value we can estimate. Some missing values we may simply not know at all!

It appears that you have correctly identified to fill in the missing values. However, check the value that you are using to replace the missing values with. Does that make sense in this context? It is not that the profit is unknown, it is that there was no money made at all.

It appears that you have correctly identified to fill in the missing values. However, check the value that you are using to replace the missing values with. Does that make sense in this context? It is not that the profit is unknown, it is that there was no money made at all.

It appears that you have replaced some of the missing values, but not all of them. If an individual grew a crop, but were unable to sell, they arguably do not have a profit so their missing values do have a value we can give them. If instead an individual never grew a crop, we can ignore their missing values.

truefeedback.text:
Great! The unprofitable crops have been given a profit of zero since they were grown but generated no income.

The crops that were never grown, so had no chance to generate income, have been set as missing. This is correct!

falsefeedback.text:
You have correctly identified which missing values should be replaced. However, the value that you have replaced them with seems to be incorrect.

Check what you have replaced the missing values with, does that make sense in this context? It is not that the profit is unknown, it is that there was no money made at all from some crops.
